WORKING

1)A LoRa-based landslide detection and warning system uses a network of sensors to monitor parameters like soil moisture, ground vibration, tilt, 
and rainfall in landslide-prone areas. These sensors transmit real-time data using LoRa (Long Range) wireless technology to a gateway, 
which then sends it to a cloud or local server. The data is analyzed using algorithms or machine learning to detect early signs of landslides.
When thresholds are exceeded, the system triggers alerts via SMS, apps, or sirens for timely evacuation.

2)The system includes sensor nodes, a LoRa gateway, and a central processing unit. It is ideal for remote or mountainous regions due to LoRa’s low power consumption,
long-range connectivity, and cost-effectiveness. Sensors can run on battery power for long periods, and data is visualized on dashboards for continuous monitoring.
Future upgrades may include AI-based models for improved prediction, enhancing disaster preparedness and response.

3)Sensor Signal Acquisition and Processing
Signal Capture and Detection
The landslide detection sensor node is designed to capture environmental signals such as ground vibration, tilt, and soil moisture. 
It includes an antenna for LoRa communication, along with sensors like accelerometers, tilt sensors, and soil moisture sensors. 
The sensors are connected to a signal conditioning circuit comprising resistors, capacitors, an operational amplifier (LM358 IC),
a transistor (BC548), and an LED indicator.

4)Environmental changes are detected and converted into analog signals. Capacitors help filter out noise, 
while resistors act as voltage dividers to ensure proper signal levels. The LM358 amplifier boosts weak sensor signals to a readable level for the microcontroller.

5)Triggering ESP32 and Display Update
Once amplified, the signal activates a BC548 transistor which turns ON an LED indicator to show activity. 
Simultaneously, this triggers the ESP32 microcontroller. Upon receiving this input,
the ESP32 updates the LCD display to show messages such as “VIBRATION DETECTED” or “SOIL MOISTURE HIGH,” alerting local users of potential landslide conditions.

6) Energy Storage in Battery
The sensor node is powered by harvested energy or solar power.
The energy is stored in a 3.7V lithium-ion battery, which acts as a buffer to maintain operations during periods of low input or at night.

7)Boost Conversion
A boost converter increases the voltage from 3.7V to 12V using components such as a MOSFET (IRFP250),
inductor (1mH), diode (1N4001), capacitor (1nF), and a BC547 transistor. The ESP32 sends PWM pulses to regulate the switching of the MOSFET,
enabling efficient voltage boosting for powering 12V components, including the LoRa module.

8) Sound and Vibration Detection (Seismic Signals)

9)Vibration Detection Using Piezoelectric Plates
In landslide-prone areas, piezoelectric plates detect ground vibration.
When seismic activity occurs, it creates stress on the plates, which generates voltage via the piezoelectric effect.
These are particularly sensitive to high-frequency vibrations, providing early detection of soil movement.

10)Factors influencing detection efficiency:
 Frequency: Plates respond best above 1 kHz.
 Intensity: Higher stress levels generate more voltage.
 Material: PZT offers superior energy conversion.
 Plate Size: Thicker or larger plates work better at lower frequencies.

11)Rectification and Filtering
The AC output from the piezo plates is converted to DC using a bridge rectifier and filtered using capacitors. 
This stable DC voltage is essential for safe energy storage and system operation.

12) Energy Storage in Battery
The DC voltage is stored in a 3.7V lithium-ion battery. Similar to RF signal energy, it is later boosted to 12V for system use.

13)Boost Conversion
The voltage is stepped up using a boost converter controlled by the ESP32’s PWM signals. 
This allows the harvested energy to power the 12V battery and all connected components reliably.

14) ESP32’s Role in the System

15) Startup Display Unit
Upon powering up, the ESP32 initializes peripherals and displays 
"LORA-BASED LANDSLIDE WARNING SYSTEM" on the LCD to confirm readiness.

16) Real-time Sensor Detection and Display Control
Sensor inputs are connected to ESP32 GPIO pins. 
The ESP32 continuously monitors them, and when a change is detected, it updates the LCD to notify about ground vibrations, 
soil shifts, or water saturation.

17)PWM Signal Generation for Boost Converters
ESP32 outputs PWM signals to control the boost converters. 
By varying the duty cycle, it adjusts the output voltage efficiently, enabling optimal energy use.

18) Power Distribution and 12V Battery Utilization
The charged 12V battery supplies power to:
 ESP32 (via 5V regulator)
 LCD Display
 Sensor Node and Signal Amplifier
 LoRa Module
 Additional alarms or indicators

19)PROGRAMMING THE ESP32

Step 1: Installing the Required Software
 Download and install the Arduino IDE from arduino.cc.
 Add the ESP32 board support URL: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/espressif/arduino-esp32/gh-pages/package_esp32_index.json
 Use Boards Manager to install the ESP32 by Espressif Systems.

Step 2: Connecting ESP32
 Use a USB cable for connection.
 Select correct board and port from the Tools menu.
 Install USB drivers (e.g., CP2102 or CH340G) if needed.

Step 3: Writing the Code
 Include libraries for LCD, LoRa, and PWM.
 Define pin mappings for sensors, PWM outputs, and display.
 Initialize sensors and peripherals in the setup() function.
 In the loop(), check sensor inputs, update display, and manage power control via PWM.

Step 4: Compiling and Uploading
 Click Verify to check for errors.
 Click Upload to flash the ESP32.
 If needed, press the BOOT button during upload.

Step 5: Testing and Debugging
 Check the startup display.
 Simulate landslide conditions to ensure sensors are detected.
 Verify PWM outputs with an oscilloscope or multimeter.
 Ensure reliable communication with the LoRa gateway.
